In C++, exceptions are objects,This allows the exception to carry 
information:

The object can contain:

an error message
an error code
a filename
a line number
any extra information

When an exception is thrown at the run time :
the exception object is created.
starts searching for a catch.
destroys all local object in the function being exited.
transfers control to the matching catch. 

*The exception object is created in a special runtime-managed *storage area*

It destroys actual stack frames one by one, running destructors, until it reaches a matching catch.

e.what() : is a way to retrieve infos from the exception object
after the exception has been caught.